
[1]replevy

   REPLEV'Y, v.t. [re and pledge. Law L. replegiabilis and replegiare.]

   1. To take back, by a writ for that purpose cattle or goods that have
   been distrained, upon giving security to try the right of distraining
   in a suit at law, and if that should be determined against the
   plaintiff, to return the cattle or goods into the hands of the
   distrainor. In this case, the person whose goods are distrained becomes
   the plaintiff, and the person distraining the defendant or avowant.

   2. To bail.
